comments.text: This case has always bothered me. Not so much that I think foul play was involved, but mostly just knowing how horrible this was for them. It's so hard to really apply logic to scenarios like this adequately. I know we like to assign a third party to senseless deaths to try to add some sense to them. It's horrible to think of the fear they would have felt. No one ever wants to assign blame to victims, it hurts the heart too much to think they could be the very figures that caused their own demise. If I were to guess, though, about the night photos by that time, they would have been paranoid and on the edge of delirium. The photos at night may be out of fear of predators. Real or imagined. Of course, like anyone else, all I can do is guess. If you are going to go hiking in your own backyard and especially in foreign areas, don't treat it lightly. Plan as if you are absolutely going to make a mistake and get lost, but try your best not to. I just don't know what to think here. RIP ladies.

comments.text:
The four suspicious deaths of the young men directly related to the case in the ensuing days to come - including the taxi driver, the son of Guide F,  and the two youg men pictured with Kris and Lisanne at the waterfall - are clear indication that the young women's disappearance was the result of foul play. The fact that each of the four young men's deaths had been ruled "accidental" despite
 overwhelming evidence to the contrary strongly suggests that authorities were dead set on sweeping the entire ordeal under the rug even to the point of eliminating any future investigations and inquiries into the related subsequent deaths, indicating that authorities were unwilling to risk any chance of someone uncovering damning information that would contradict the nation's offical stance on the women's deaths.

A cover-up is further suggested by the death threats and bullying received by the parents of Kris when they attempted to pursue their own investigation with the help of 16 Dutch detectives and 8 scent dogs. The fact that they were ambushed by authorities wielding machetes as they approached the entrance to the trail and threatened to be killed unless they dropped the investigation and accepted the stafe ruling adds to the cerfainty of foul play.   The fact that subsequent investigations by amateurs and writers were also met with the same threats indicates that whatever happened to Kris and Lisanne will remain a mystery forever until someone at some point gets drunk and reveals too much to the wrong people - or the right people.

comments.text: Four months ago, the You Tube channel "The Pianistra Puzzle" explained how and why the night pictures came to be. This can be found in their video entitled "Return to the Night Location." They also show four different possible routes taken by the girls after the crossed over the continental divide in their video entitled "What Happened to Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon?" Between these two videos, almost all of the questions regarding what happened to Kris and Lisanne can be answered. I believe the girls continued on the trail after the summit because they had learned there were waterfalls further on. I believe they took the route entitled "Option 2" in the latter video. I believe they got to the first cable bridge and attempted to cross it. Here, one or both were hurt seriously in the attempt. The injury (or injuries) was great enough to cause the first 112 call. I think the girls limped back to the "second paddock" hoping that the open area of the paddock would aid in an unobstructed signal. Here is where the second unsuccessful emergency call was made. The girls then powered off their phones to save battery and hunkered down for the night. In the morning I believe they headed back up the trail that they had come down, hoping to gain a signal at a higher elevation.  At this point I believe they made a mistake that sealed their fate. Instead of going back up the trail the way they had come, they went off onto the trail that branches off to the southeast (this junction is labelled as El Coco on the map.) From there they continued to Rio Mamei. By this point they would have known they had made a wrong turn and they were in fact lost. I believe the girls could hear the search helicopters and knew people were looking for them. Ultimately, I believe they used the camera after moonset to try to create a light beacon hoping that someone, somewhere would see it. After this, I believe Kris passed away. Lisanne took her phone and continued on until she lost her footing and died on the rocks of the Rio Mamei. Finally, both bodies and their possessions were washed downstream during the rainy season. The bodies were shredded by the current and the rocks and Kris's shorts and the back pack came to rest where they did.

comments.text:
In the end, I think they let themselves be trapped by the arrival of night.
After photo 508, I think Lisanne dropped her camera on the ground or in the water. Making it unusable. Despite everything, they continued a little on the trail and at one point they decided to go back but they saw that the light was dropping very quickly in certain portions since we are in the tropics and the sun rises at 6:00 in the morning and goes to bed at 6:00 p.m. all year round.
They are therefore on their way back but they realize that they need at least two or three hours of walking and a large part of this walk will have to take place at night. They worry because they know the places they have already passed and know that without a flashlight, in the dark of night, it is very difficult and distressing.
Thatâ€™s when they try to call for help, if only to say where they are because they didnâ€™t tell anyone in the end. They just said they were going for a walk.
But impossible to contact anyone: no network.
At that moment, they were not injured, nor pursued by anyone, just anxious at the idea of â€‹â€‹returning at night. The wisest thing would have been to land somewhere in open ground and resolve to spend the night there and leave the next morning at first light. In a video, the mother of Kriss who came on the trail explains that she is absolutely sure that if one of the girls had been injured, they would have stayed on the trail and waited. The problem actually is that he There was no injury or other, only from being trapped by the time and the arrival of night, and also from not having warned anyone.

I think that by trying to retrace the path at night, she had a high chance of getting lost, falling, slipping, etc. Which at night reinforces the seriousness of the situation.
So they get lost. And the second catastrophe arrives, no one knows where they went or more precisely, no one knows that they continued beyond the Mirador, towards the North on the path. So by the time we organize the research, a lot of time will pass. And we will have to wait until April 6 for research to be done on the other side of the Mirador. That is to say that the girls got lost, that they continued to move during these 6 days, if only to try to find a place with a little network. And obviously in 6 days, without food or very little (?), without water except that of the river (risk of diarrhea that one of the girls already had not long before during the stay), without being able to make a fire. Fear, anxiety, stress, exhaustion...etc. When the search begins beyond the Mirador, the girls are already in a bad state in my opinion.

On April 8, they have been in the jungle for 7 days! It is said that you can survive 3 minutes without breathing, 3 days without drinking and 3 weeks without eating. I think they were in the state of people who go on hunger strike. They must have remained in bed, half lucid. One may be more affected than the other.
On the night of April 8, they heard noise, perhaps light signals in the sky or something else coming from the search teams. I think Lisanne understands that you have to try something to stand out. They are obviously in no condition to scream or anything. So she takes out the camera which she had put to dry and which she had not tried to get it working again since. And it works again. This is possible if the device fell into water and was quickly removed from the water. In time he can works again. So she decides to use it to make flash shots towards the sky. Obviously it takes photos at the same time but the goal is the flash.
She is exhausted and at the same time held by the hope of being seen. She awkwardly directs the flash towards the ground a few times which causes her to accidentally take a photo of Kriss' hair who is probably lying sleepy next to her or her head on Lisanne's legs.
But it doesn't work, the noises and signals go away. The only hope for days has vanished. We didn't see them.

I think they end up dying of exhaustion and hunger. Not necessarily at the same time.

Subsequently, the rainy season set in, causing rivers to swell and causing flooding. Their bodies were carried away by the waves, disintegrating as they decomposed....

RQ / *Contrary to what has often been said, the bag was dirty and damp when they found it. The items they contained were also damp and the devices were unusable. The Dutch experts had difficulty using them; it was easier with SD cards.
*The fact that the young women took off their bras appears normal  considering the conditions in which they were (heat, humidity, etc.).
*The shorts again were not found dry and folded neatly on a stone. It was dirty, wet and with holes.
*There have never been 70 pin code attempts in 1 day as has been said. In fact it was the Dutch experts who determined that since the phone was put into service, there had been 70 unsuccessful pin code attempts. That is to say that since the girl had been using her cell phone, it had happened to her 70 times of making a mistake when typing your code.
*There has never been a scrap of human flesh found with bones, which seemed impossible as decomposition would have made it disappear very quickly. In fact this scrap of flesh was analyzed and it was beef.
